-- | See <a>Podman.Tutorial</a> to learn how to use this library.
--   
--   Here is the recommended way to import this library:
--   
--   <pre>
--   {-# LANGUAGE OverloadedStrings #-}
--   
--   import Podman
--   </pre>
--   
--   This module re-exports the rest of the library.
--   
--   <a>Podman.Types</a> provides data types generated from the swagger
--   definitions.
--   
--   <a>Podman.Internal</a> provides utility function to further decode API
--   response. Internal is exposed for testing purpose and it shouldn't be
--   used.
--   
--   <h1>Notes</h1>
--   
--   Some notes on the API. And on Podman generally. (Particularly on ttys,
--   and attaching and detaching from them, since that's quite fiddly.)
--   
--   <ul>
--   <li>When creating a container, <a>_specGeneratorstdin</a> is
--   equivalent to "podman container create -i ...". However, it
--   <i>doesn't</i> automatically allocate a tty. You need
--   <a>_specGeneratorterminal</a> for that (the equivalent of passing "-t"
--   to "podman container create").</li>
--   <li>If attaching to a container, a tty needs to be allocated if you
--   want to <i>detach</i> again using the "detach keys". See <a>container
--   attach man page</a> for details of "container attach", and <a>this
--   "wontfix" issue</a> which says detaching from a non-tty container is
--   not supported.</li>
--   <li>The Podman API notes on <a>"containers/{ctr_name}/attach"</a> are
--   not very complete. It looks like the Docker Engine API docs have
--   additional information (see
--   <a>https://docs.docker.com/engine/api/v1.41/#operation/ContainerAttach</a>).
--   Namely:<ul><li>When attaching to a container, the HTTP connection is
--   "hijacked" so as to transport stdin, stdout, and stderr on the same
--   socket.</li><li>The response from the daemon for an attach request
--   is:<pre> HTTP/1.1 200 OK Content-Type:
--   application/vnd.docker.raw-stream [STREAM] </pre>After the headers and
--   two new lines, the TCP connection can now be used for raw,
--   bidirectional communication between the client and server.</li><li>The
--   client will (should?) send <tt>Upgrade: tcp</tt> and <tt>Connection:
--   Upgrade</tt> headers in its request.</li><li>If that happens server
--   will (should?) respond with <tt>HTTP/1.1 101 UPGRADED</tt>, and
--   <tt>Connection: Upgrade</tt> and <tt>Upgrade: tcp</tt>
--   headers.</li><li>Those "upgrade" headers are supposed to be a hint to
--   any HTTP proxies about what's going on; but I suspect a fair few
--   proxies just won't be able to cope with the socket being hijacked in
--   this way.</li><li>See the Docker API documentation for more info (e.g.
--   on the stream format).</li></ul></li>
--   </ul>
